<br>
You asked for it. I accept your challenge!!!!<br>
Hey? What About Dex for Casters?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://eq.crgaming.com/viewarticle.asp?Article=607">eq.crgaming.com/viewartic...rticle=607</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
&quot;GZ ON CASTING RECOVERY, JANUARY 4, 2000&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
quote:<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Your chance to recover casting is calculated solely on your Channelling Skill. <br>
Dexterity only affects Channelling in relation to raising your skill in it. How quickly your raise your Channelling ability is determined by a combination of Dexterity and Intelligence. <br>
<br>
Dexterity does not affect your chance to actually recover casting. <br>
<br>
Agility doesn't affect Channelling, or casting recovery in any way whatsoever. <br>
<br>
If you cast a spell which you are 5 or more levels higher than when you obtained it (eg: root is a level 4 spell, so if you are level 9 or higher) you get a Channelling boost, ie: a higher chance to recover casting if interrupted. <br>
<br>
Player controlled movement will, in most circumstances, break a spell with no chance to recover. <br>
<br>
Movement caused by a monster hitting you while you are casting a spell gets a chance to recover the casting. <br>
<br>
Your skill level in a specific type of spell (eg: Evocation) doesn't affect your chance of recovery. However, this will affect your chance to fizzle the spell. <br>
<br>
Any Specialization skill you have in the type of spell being cast will not affect recovery, however it will have a chance to reduce mana cost, and lower the fizzle rate.<br>
<br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
<br>
GENERAL STATS<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://eq.crgaming.com/viewarticle.asp?Article=1227">eq.crgaming.com/viewartic...ticle=1227</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
&quot;STATS EXPLAINED, APRIL 9, 2000&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
quote:<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
In working with the people doing the strategy guide for Kunark we decided to provide them with general information as to what the stats do. <br>
I'm going to post them here. <br>
This is a change in the sense that we were not going to discuss them or release more info. We changed our minds. <br>
<br>
That said, we're not posting any formulas, and it's absolutely true that some stats have considerably more direct impact on gameplay than others. <br>
<br>
We're posting this for clarification, and because previous explanations have not been accurate (manual, etc). We will not, however, engage in debate and our stance on how much some stats affect game play is that it's by design to inhibit some aspects of twinking. Are there better attribute systems out there? Yeah, but we're not going to change something as fundamental as a stat system in EQ after the game's been out for more than a year. <br>
<br>
Anyway, here you go: <br>
<br>
DEX: how quickly you learn weapon skills; how often weapon will proc; how quickly you learn rogue skills; how hard you hit with bows <br>
<br>
STR: determines how much you can carry; influences maximum and average damage; influences how quickly you learn many offensive skills <br>
<br>
STA: affects how many hit points you have, how long you can hold your breath <br>
<br>
INT: directly affects how quickly you can learn most skills; affects the amount of mana for bards and all mages, as well as shadow knights <br>
<br>
WIS: affects the amount of mana the priest classes have, also rangers; also affects how quickly you can learn many skills if your wisdom is higher than INT. <br>
<br>
CHA: affects amount you will be paid for goods by NPC merchants, and how much they will pay you; affects the saving throw on certain bard and enchanter spells (charms in particular) <br>
<br>
AGI: affects how quickly you can learn some defensive skills, how difficult it is to hit you as well as how much damage you take when you are hit <br>
<br>
- Brad<br>
<br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
<br>
On Charisma In Particular:<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://eq.crgaming.com/viewarticle.asp?Article=4882">eq.crgaming.com/viewartic...ticle=4882</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
&quot;CHARISMA &amp; LULLS, NOVEMBER 5, 2002&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
quote:<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Source: The Concert Hall.<br>
<br>
We don't usually get too far into specifics in favor of people discovering the usefulness themselves. <br>
<br>
Unfortunately, with an ability as subtle as this one, Charisma's impact is hard to discover, and would likely continue on into the annals of EQ history as &quot;useless.&quot; <br>
<br>
That said -- On the Lull/Harmony series, which has recently been rewritten, there are two checks, as I imagine most everyone knows already. <br>
<br>
Is the effect resisted? <br>
<br>
If the effect is resisted, will the NPC get angry and tell its friends that it's time for a BardSnack(tm), or will it ignore what just happened? <br>
<br>
Charisma is the sole determinant in the second check. It doesn't affect the first. <br>
<br>
As for the in-game justification: If it likes you enough, it might find itself compelled to forgive you for trying to pull a fast one on it. <br>
<br>
Hope that helps. <br>
<br>
Best, <br>
<br>
Scott Hartsman <br>
Technical Director, EverQuest<br>
<br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://eq.crgaming.com/archives.asp?Day=5&Month=11&Year=2002&ID=4884&Action=View">eq.crgaming.com/archives....ction=View</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
<br>
quote:<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
November 5, 2002 <br>
<br>
<br>
CHARISMA &amp; LULLS PART 2<br>
Clerics &amp; Enchanters may also want to note that we recently confirmed with Scott Hartsman that their Lull spells are also Charisma based for determining whether or not an NPC will aggro on resist.<br>
<br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://eq.crgaming.com/viewarticle.asp?Article=4063">eq.crgaming.com/viewartic...ticle=4063</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
&quot;DALLAS FAN FAIRE MAGIC PANEL, JANUARY 29, 2002&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
quote:<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Necromancers have really low charisma but get Fears and Charms which need it? Doesn't this seem strange?<br>
Charisma has nothing to do with resist rates on Fear spells, and has only a minor help on the Charms. It's got a lot more to do with levels for both of those, so the Necromancers don't really have too many problems with that.<br>
<br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
<br>
A clarification of the above is here:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://eq.crgaming.com/viewarticle.asp?Article=4451">eq.crgaming.com/viewartic...ticle=4451</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
&quot;BOSTON PRODUCERS &amp; DEVELOPERS, AUGUST 7, 2002&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
quote:<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Is Charisma actually taken into account on mesmerizations and charms?<br>
Yes it is. It varies on a number of spells to its actual usefulness but it does have a use. There are different levels of charisma for different classes. The system does take into account that an Enchanter should have a higher charisma than say a Necromancer. It’s unfair to expect masters of the undead to be entirely charismatic<br>
<br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
<br>
On Tradeskills and Stats:<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://eq.crgaming.com/viewarticle.asp?Article=4074">eq.crgaming.com/viewartic...ticle=4074</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
&quot;TRADESKILLS: FROM THE DALLAS FAN FAIRE, FEBRUARY 1, 2002&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
quote:<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Regarding Trivials. On some items I will succeed a bunch of times, then I will fail a bunch in a row. Even though sometimes it says it is trivial.<br>
There is always a 5% chance of failure regardless of your skill or its trivial. But there is no stat which has an effect on success rate, stats just impact on how quickly you learn the skill.<br>
<br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://eq.crgaming.com/viewarticle.asp?Article=4274">eq.crgaming.com/viewartic...ticle=4274</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
&quot;TRADESKILL PANEL TRANSCRIPT, MAY 6, 2002&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
quote:<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Which stat is used for raising skills in Blacksmithing?<br>
Whichever is the highest of Intelligence, Wisdom or Strength.<br>
<br>
What other skills have secondary skills like Smithing?<br>
<br>
Fletching runs off Dexterity, Jewelry runs off Dexterity, Tailoring will run off Dexterity soon. Basically that means whichever is highest of Intelligence, Wisdom or Dexterity will be the stat checked for chances to raise skill.<br>
<br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
<br>
There, how was that? <br>
<br>
